You will need quite a few things to run these experiments.
1) python
2) docker
3) node
4) a custom cURL build with HTTP3 support (not included in the standard Ubuntu)
5) a bunch of specifically open ports?

Steps to running the servers.
1) Have docker installed
2) in the ./h2o directory, run "sudo docker compose build" to create the server images.
3) run "sudo docker compose up" to create the server containers.

	- To change what ports are hosting the servers on your local machine, change the "xxxx" field in the xxxx:yyyy HOST:PORT in the "ports" tag
	of the docker-compose.yml file.
	- The default host:port mappings for the HTTP3 endpoints are:
		h2o-server: 8444
		h2o-pico-server: 8446
		h2o-cubic-server: 8448
	the servers will host files on these ports via QUIC/HTTP3 (NO TCP FALLBACK).
	an alternative TCP host is available with every container and is hosted with the same hostname but subtract 1 from the QUIC port number.
	
these servers should be accessible as:
	https://localhost:8444/file.txt
	(replace file.txt with any of the payload names).
	
4) to kill these servers, run sudo docker compose down in the ./h2o directory.



5) in EACH ols-docker-env folder, run "sudo docker compose up" to run its container.
the docker process should download the base image and run it. all of the configuration to change the server settings
is already provided; each folder is named after the congestion control algorithm used in the container.

To change what ports are hosting the servers on your local machine, similarly change the "xxxx" field in the xxxx:yyyy HOST:PORT in the "ports" tag
of the docker-compose.yml file, except this would have to be done on the individual folder level. Ports hosts BOTH HTTP/2 and HTTP/3.
The default host:port mappings are:
litespeed-default: 27015
litespeed-bbr: 27016
litespeed-cubic: 27017

these servers should be accessible as:
	https://localhost:27015/file.txt
	(replace file.txt with any of the payload names).

6) run "sudo docker compose down" in a container's folder to kill it.
7) to access the admin server for configurations, access the server with the special "1776x" port noted in the docker-compose.yml file.
By default these are
litespeed-default: 17760
litespeed-bbr: 17761
litespeed-cubic: 17762
the login is
username: admin
password: superstrongpassword

(don't even try doing it on the aws endpoint. i changed the password)

--------------------------------
Running the HTTP3 Client/Network Experiments
--------------------------------
This requires 2 things.
a) a custom cURL binary with http3 integration, which can be downloaded from
https://github.com/stunnel/static-curl
or the one used here.

b) a python virtual environment, inside of which the source for the test files is placed,
which is probably the one pulled from https://github.com/a-tol/quic-benchmarks

1) download the cURL binary.
2) you can query either the locally hosted endpoint from earlier with
	/path/to/curl -k [--http3-only | --http3 ] [endpoint] [--output FILE]
	or one of (hopefully still hosted) endpoints, like
	/path/to/curl --http3-only -k https://ec2-13-222-23-193.compute-1.amazonaws.com:8444/file.txt

3) pull the tester source code from github or use the included folder (if it still works)
4) make a python virtual environment
	mkdir env
	python -m venv ./env
5) move the tester code into the environment
6) cd chrome, npm i
7) install dependencies in ./quic-benchmarks/:
	../bin/pip install -r ./reqirements.txt
8) sudo bash run_benchmarks.sh
